lims are constantly negotiating the differences between families for whom faith and culture were matters of honor and North America’s youth culture, with its emphasis on questioning, exploring, and inventing one’s own destiny."—from the Introduction by Eboo PatelIn Growing Up Muslim, Andrew Garrod and Robert Kilkenny present fourteen personal essays by college students of the Muslim faith who are themselves immigrants or are the children of immigrants to the United States. In their essays, the students grapple with matters of ethnicity, religious prejudice and misunderstanding, and what is termed Islamophobia. The fact of 9/11 and subsequent surveillance and suspicion of Islamic Americans (particularly those hailing from the Middle East and the Asian Subcontinent) have had a profound effect on these students, their families, and their communities of origin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aElectronic books. 0aMuslim college studentszNew HampshirezHanovervBiography. 0aMuslim youthxEducation (Higher)zNew HampshirezHanover. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 4aEducation & History Of Education. 7aYOUNG ADULT NONFICTION / Biography & Autobiography / Cultural, Ethnic & Regional.2bisacsh  aAdolescents.  aAmerican multiculturalism.  aArab American.  aAspiration.  aAssimilation.  aBelonging.  aIslamic Americans.  aIslamic Studies youth.  aIslamic Studies.  aIslamic youth.  aIslamophobia.  aMuslim American Experience after 9/11.  aMuslim American Experience.  aafter 9/11.  aamerican islam.  aamerican like me.  aamerican muslim studies.  aamerican racism.  aanti-racism.  aautobiography.  abooks about freshman.  achildren of immigrants.  acollege students.  acommon reading.  aessay anthologies.  aessays.  aethnic studies.  afreshm